The paper deals with algorithmic techniques for solving energy games, which are a type of two-player game played on a graph. This falls under the category of computational game theory (cs.GT). The paper also involves the use of hyperplane separation techniques, which are commonly used in computational geometry (cs.CG) and linear programming (cs.DS). The running time analysis of the algorithm involves complexity theory (cs.CC), and the use of dynamic programming and memoization techniques suggests an artificial intelligence (cs.AI) component. Finally, the paper involves the study of graph algorithms and optimization problems, which could fall under the categories of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM).
